# Frontend Testing

Frontend testing verifies that components render correctly, respond to user interactions, manage state properly, and meet accessibility requirements. Test at the right level: unit tests for logic, component tests for UI behavior, E2E tests for critical user flows.

## Testing Pyramid

| Level | Tool | Speed | Scope |
|-------|------|-------|-------|
| Unit | Vitest | Fast | Functions, hooks, utilities |
| Component | Vitest + Testing Library | Medium | Single component behavior |
| Integration | Vitest + Testing Library | Medium | Multi-component interactions |
| E2E | Playwright | Slow | Full user flows in a browser |
| Accessibility | axe-core + Playwright | Medium | WCAG compliance audits |

## Unit Tests

Vitest for testing pure functions, custom hooks, and utilities:

```typescript
// utils/format.test.ts
import { describe, it, expect } from "vitest";
import { formatCurrency, truncateText } from "./format";

describe("formatCurrency", () => {
  it("formats USD with two decimal places", () => {
    expect(formatCurrency(1234.5, "USD")).toBe("$1,234.50");
  });

  it("handles zero", () => {
    expect(formatCurrency(0, "USD")).toBe("$0.00");
  });
});
```

Test custom hooks with `renderHook`:

```typescript
import { renderHook, act } from "@testing-library/react";
import { useCounter } from "./useCounter";

it("increments counter", () => {
  const { result } = renderHook(() => useCounter());
  act(() => result.current.increment());
  expect(result.current.count).toBe(1);
});
```

See [[frontend/react#hooks]] for custom hook patterns and [[frontend/state]] for testing state stores.

## Component Tests

React Testing Library tests components by simulating user behavior, not inspecting implementation:

```tsx
import { render, screen } from "@testing-library/react";
import userEvent from "@testing-library/user-event";
import { LoginForm } from "./LoginForm";

describe("LoginForm", () => {
  it("submits with email and password", async () => {
    const onSubmit = vi.fn();
    render(<LoginForm onSubmit={onSubmit} />);

    await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText("Email"), "user@example.com");
    await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText("Password"), "secret123");
    await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button", { name: "Sign in" }));

    expect(onSubmit).toHaveBeenCalledWith({
      email: "user@example.com",
      password: "secret123",
    });
  });

  it("shows validation error for empty email", async () => {
    render(<LoginForm onSubmit={vi.fn()} />);
    await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button", { name: "Sign in" }));
    expect(screen.getByText("Email is required")).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

Key principles:
- Query by role, label, or text — not by class name or test ID
- Use `userEvent` over `fireEvent` for realistic interactions
- Test behavior ("what the user sees") not implementation ("what state changed")
- Wrap state providers if the component uses [[frontend/state#zustand]] or [[frontend/state#context-api]]

## End-to-End Tests

Playwright tests full user flows in real browsers:

```typescript
// tests/checkout.spec.ts
import { test, expect } from "@playwright/test";

test("complete checkout flow", async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto("/products");
  await page.getByRole("button", { name: "Add to cart" }).first().click();
  await page.getByRole("link", { name: "Cart (1)" }).click();

  await expect(page.getByRole("heading", { name: "Your Cart" })).toBeVisible();
  await page.getByRole("button", { name: "Checkout" }).click();

  await page.getByLabel("Email").fill("user@example.com");
  await page.getByLabel("Card number").fill("4242424242424242");
  await page.getByRole("button", { name: "Pay" }).click();

  await expect(page.getByText("Order confirmed")).toBeVisible();
});
```

Playwright features:
- Cross-browser (Chromium, Firefox, WebKit)
- Auto-waiting for elements
- Built-in assertions with `expect`
- Network interception for mocking APIs
- Trace viewer for debugging failures

## Accessibility Testing

Automate accessibility audits with axe-core in Playwright:

```typescript
import { test, expect } from "@playwright/test";
import AxeBuilder from "@axe-core/playwright";

test("homepage has no accessibility violations", async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto("/");
  const results = await new AxeBuilder({ page })
    .withTags(["wcag2a", "wcag2aa"])
    .analyze();
  expect(results.violations).toEqual([]);
});
```

Run axe on every page in CI. See [[frontend/accessibility#wcag-checklist]] for the full WCAG 2.1 AA checklist and [[frontend/accessibility#testing-tools]] for manual testing tools.

## Coverage

Vitest has built-in coverage via `v8` or `istanbul`:

```bash
# Run with coverage
npx vitest run --coverage

# vitest.config.ts
export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    coverage: {
      provider: "v8",
      reporter: ["text", "html", "lcov"],
      thresholds: {
        branches: 80,
        functions: 80,
        lines: 80,
        statements: 80,
      },
    },
  },
});
```

Aim for 80%+ coverage on business-critical code. 100% coverage is not a goal — focus on testing behavior, not lines.

## Test Commands

```bash
# Vitest
npx vitest              # Watch mode
npx vitest run          # Single run (CI)
npx vitest run --coverage  # With coverage

# Playwright
npx playwright test     # Run all E2E tests
npx playwright test --ui  # Interactive UI mode
npx playwright show-report  # View HTML report
```
